 We have the following transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=q+ip,\hspace{1em}P=Q^{*}=q-ip,
\]

\end_inset

and in order to see if this transformation is canonical we know that
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\left(q,p\right)\rightarrow\left(Q,P\right)$
\end_inset

 is canonical if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[Q_{i},Q_{j}\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=0,\hspace{1em}\left[P_{i},P_{j}\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=0,\hspace{1em}\left[Q_{i},P_{j}\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=\delta_{ij}.
\]

\end_inset

But in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j=1$
\end_inset

 which implies that the first two Poisson Brackets vanish, then the only
 thing left to calculate is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[Q,P\right]_{\left(q,p\right)},
\]

\end_inset

which is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[Q,P\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=\frac{\partial Q}{\partial q}\frac{\partial P}{\partial p}-\frac{\partial Q}{\partial p}\frac{\partial P}{\partial q},
\]

\end_inset

Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial Q}{\partial q}=1,\hspace{1em}\frac{\partial Q}{\partial p}=i,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial P}{\partial q}=1,\hspace{1em}\frac{\partial P}{\partial p}=-i
\]

\end_inset

then, the Poisson bracket becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[Q,P\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=\left(1\right)\left(-i\right)-\left(i\right)\left(1\right)=-2i,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left[Q,P\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=-2i,
\]

\end_inset

and then the transformation is 
\series bold
not canonical
\series default
.
 On the other hand if instead we consider the following transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=\frac{i}{\sqrt{2i}}\left(q+ip\right),\hspace{1em}P=\frac{i}{\sqrt{2i}}\left(q-ip\right),
\]

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial Q}{\partial q}=\frac{i}{\sqrt{2i}},\hspace{1em}\frac{\partial Q}{\partial p}=\frac{i^{2}}{\sqrt{2i}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial P}{\partial q}=\frac{i}{\sqrt{2i}},\hspace{1em}\frac{\partial P}{\partial p}=\frac{-i^{2}}{\sqrt{2i}},
\]

\end_inset

and now, the Poisson bracket becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[Q,P\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=\left(\frac{i}{\sqrt{2i}}\right)\left(\frac{-i^{2}}{\sqrt{2i}}\right)-\left(\frac{i^{2}}{\sqrt{2i}}\right)\left(\frac{i}{\sqrt{2i}}\right)=\frac{i}{2i}+\frac{i}{2i},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left[Q,P\right]_{\left(q,p\right)}=1,
\]

\end_inset

and then, 
\series bold
the transformation is canonical
\series default
.
